	<clause id="_sources_of_uncertainty_due_to_the_source" obligation="normative"><title>Sources of Uncertainty Due to the Source</title><clause id="_blackbody_emissivity" obligation="normative"><title>Blackbody emissivity</title><p id="_03e5c2c9-4149-495a-aafa-4260fa3c6767">The Monte-Carlo method is usually used for estimating a high-temperature blackbody’s effective emissivity <eref type="inline" bibitemid="sapritsky" citeas="[53]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="prokhorov" citeas="[54]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="hartmann-taubert2002" citeas="[55]"/>. The uncertainty in the emissivity can by estimated using the same method by varying the cavity’s surface reflectance and temperature distributions. Typical emissivities of large-area variable-temperature blackbodies in the visible are in the range from 0.999 to 0.9997 with a standard uncertainty of 0.0002 to 0.0005 <eref type="inline" bibitemid="khlevnoy-samoylov" citeas="[56]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="yoon-gibson2003" citeas="[57]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="hartmann2010" citeas="[58]"/>. The typical emissivity of HTFPs is 0.9997 with a standard uncertainty of 0.0001 to 0.0002 <eref type="inline" bibitemid="khlevnoy-grigoryeva" citeas="[59]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="yamada" citeas="[60]"/>. In the case of HTFP thermodynamic temperature measurement, the influence of the furnace cavity on the FP blackbody cavity must be taken into account <eref type="inline" bibitemid="bloembergen2008" citeas="[61]"/>.</p>
	<p id="_8f1e8a72-de98-4a9e-a904-b91aa017569d">The blackbody emissivity and the blackbody temperature measured with a filter radiometer are related by <xref target="eq12"/>. However, for estimation of the temperature uncertainty component associated with the emissivity, we can assume that the filter radiometer spectral bandpass is narrow enough that the monochromatic approximation can be applied. For typical wavelengths and temperatures, the Wien approximation can also be applied. Therefore, the corresponding temperature uncertainty component arising from the emissivity uncertainty is given by</p>
	<formula id="eq67">
	<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>u</mi></mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>ɛ</mi></mstyle></mrow></msub><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>λ</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><msub><mrow><mi>u</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>rel</mtext></mrow></msub><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>ɛ</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mtext>BB</mtext></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced><mi>,</mi></math></stem>
	</formula>
